{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515669"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:33:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:33:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12469"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12469","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12469"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.25,0.45,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4976"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113873"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4976","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4976"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12469"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95892"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"2877"},{"type":"tags","id":"3724"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8226"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8847"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26223"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42760"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43333"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44287"},{"type":"contributions","id":"47310"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113873","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113873"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 40-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with sudden-onset sharp chest pain that started one hour ago. The pain is worse on inspiration. She also reports shortness of breath for the past hour, noting that she found it unusually difficult to walk her dogs this morning. She has no cough or haemoptysis. She has a medical history of systemic lupus erythematosus, for which she takes hydroxychloroquine. She uses a Mirena intrauterine device for heavy menstrual bleeding. She has had no recent travel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly distressed. Her pulse rate is 102/min, blood pressure 142/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 90% on oxygen 2 L/min via nasal prongs, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Heart sounds are dual with no murmurs. Chest is clear to auscultation. Her abdomen and calves are soft and non-tender.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer urine pregnancy test is negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be most appropriate to diagnose the underlying cause of her current problem?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-dsDNA antibodies","D-dimer","Lupus anticoagulant","vWF antigen levels","Rheumatoid factor"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis clinical presentation is most consistent with a pulmonary embolus. Her history of systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) puts her at increased risk for antiphospholipid syndrome, a pro-thrombotic state that can predispose to unprovoked pulmonary emboli.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA diagnosis of antiphospholipid syndrome is confirmed by clinical and laboratory criteria. The clinical criteria are: vascular thrombosis (venous or arterial) or pregnancy morbidity (recurrent miscarriage, foetal death or premature birth). The laboratory criteria are: \u003Cstrong\u003Elupus anticoagulant\u003C/strong\u003E positive, anti-cardiolipin antibody positive, or beta 2 glycoprotein antibody positive on two occasions at least 12 weeks apart.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-dsDNA antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are helpful to diagnose SLE, but she already has a confirmed diagnosis of this condition, so repeating them is not useful. They do mirror disease activity, but she has no clinical evidence of a flare of SLE at this time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ED-dimer\u003C/strong\u003E is a useful screening test for pulmonary embolism in low-risk patients, but it has poor specificity and would likely be elevated in this patient due to her underlying SLE. Testing for antiphospholipid syndrome would be more useful as it would guide long-term management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVon Willebrand disease, diagnosed via \u003Cstrong\u003EvWF antigen levels\u003C/strong\u003E, would result in bleeding due to dysfunctional vWF and thus impaired platelet adhesion. It is not a prothrombotic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid factor\u003C/strong\u003E is an antibody used in the diagnosis of rheumatoid arthritis. It would not help diagnose the cause of thrombosis in this patient with known SLE.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["SLE is commonly associated with antiphospholipid syndrome","Lupus Anticoagulant, Anti-Cardiolipin Antibodies, and Beta-2 Glycoprotein Antibodies are the diagnostic tests for Antiphospholipid Syndrome","Pleuritic chest pain and hypoxia in a patient with SLE should raise suspicion for pulmonary embolism"],"references":["Tektonidou MG, Andreoli L, Limper M, Amoura Z, Cervera R, Costedoat-Chalumeau C, et al. EULAR recommendations for the management of antiphospholipid syndrome in adults. Ann Rheum Dis. 2019 May; 78: 1296-1304."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95892"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12469"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"i